&quot;how would you feel if the President of the US televised that there was no god?&quot;<br>
<br>
Man, it wouldn’t surprise me one bit to tell the truth. Bush is showing himself to be a pushover...and wishy-washy. But to actually hear it said by the Prez. would offend me. <br>
<br>
To argue theology is one thing, but to argue existence vs. non-existence is another. Most middle-of-the-road &quot;Supreme Being&quot; believers extend a hard-core believer the benefit of the doubt...the atheist does not. For the hard-core believer to hear an atheist argue that there is no God is like telling a 5-year-old there is no Santa. Although the believer will contend that the atheist lacks in spiritual enlightenment and faith, they cannot refute the carnal knowledge. Believers tend to take more offense when told they believe in the Tooth Fairy, IMO.<br>
<br>
Quath: &quot;I would say natural liberty is the freedom to try to survive and prosper. This can work out in many ways like predator/prey or cooperation that benefits the involved parties. So for cows, there is a little of both. We are their predators. However, they are a very successful specias because we value them and do not try to eat them into extinction.&quot;<br>
<br>
Lurikeen: &quot;In my view we are all animals preying upon each other. This all goes to the root of our basic biological functions and natural selection. We humans just happen to be the most successfull species for the time being. Putting the issue crudely into perspective... we are top dog and can eat whatsoever we choose. I have found that we usually feel discomfort eating species we use for pets, or we believe have a certain degree of intelligence. However, again, this is all part of our basic animalistic nature. That nature, viewed in and of itself, is amoral. It is that very nature that has guaranteed our success as a species.&quot;<br>
<br>
I hear a bit of 'survival of the fittest&quot; in both your statements and I agree to a certain extent. However, I ask that we apply &quot;S.o.t.f.&quot; to child sweatshops in China and to slavery in America's early history. If God did not give all men and women freedom, then freedom is only something created by man for man. To say 'inherently born' with certain human rights would be just opinion and not a fact. In other words, we are only free cause we are the stronger species and we wish to call ourselves free and we wish that every man be free.<br>
<br>
Imo, and in the opinion of several of the founders, God intended for us to be free and all inherent human rights come from the grace of God. Without this grace.. we could overtake one another, putting the weaker in captivity and bondage (like early American's did with slaves). If men dictate what freedom is, then freedom can be taken away. That deep inter feeling that we are suppose to be and meant to be free means nothing when it is merely our desire to be free and that we maintain our freedom with dominating force (Survival of the fittest).<br>
<br>
