<br>
Rheaton, you write as though there is only one type of religious person (the Christian) and one type of non-religious person (the Atheist). Your generalizations don't make much sense to me, since the religious landscape is not as cut and dry as you portend it to be. Furthermore, the point was that you would be <b><i>offended</i></b>. Why is it that you think all of us non-Christians want to hear your christian prayers and dogmas? What, you can be offended, but we can't?<br>
<br>
<i>"If God did not give all men and women freedom, then freedom is only something created by man for man. To say 'inherently born' with certain human rights would be just opinion and not a fact."</i><br>
<br>
Much like the existence of god being your opinion? Again, we evolved in a state of natural liberty. What does that mean? It means when you were born you had no beliefs. You had no government or religion. You were naked. I think that is pretty much factual.<br>
<br>
<i>"In other words, we are only free cause we are the stronger species and we wish to call ourselves free and we wish that every man be free."</i><br>
<br>
See the above statement.<br>
<br>
<i>"Imo, and in the opinion of several of the founders, God intended for us to be free and all inherent human rights come from the grace of God. Without this grace.. we could overtake one another, putting the weaker in captivity and bondage (like early American's did with slaves). If men dictate what freedom is, then freedom can be taken away."</i><br>
<br>
Again, you are missing the underlying premise that of "natural liberty": the state of nature. "Human rights" are the advantages provided to us a species. Notice, we as a species measure equality and subordination based upon <i>intellect</i> and type of species. Rights are not given by a god as much as people who want to justify their view of life invoke a god for the purpose of bringing legitamacy to their view. However, such an invocation is misplaced at best and dishonest at worst. BTW, I recall that the founding fathers (especially Paine, Franklin, Jefferson, Madison) held a strong Lockean view of politics. That is, they would argue much as I am now sans evolutionary theory, since it was yet to be discovered.<br>
<br>
We are free because of the state of nature. It is the laws we create that bind us; hence, government is a necessary evil. <p><center><font face="arial" color="CCFFFF">Lurikeen Mali'Kyre</FONT></center><center><table style='Filter: Shadow(Color=#150517, Direction=225)'><tr><td><span class='Necromancer'><font size=2 color="red" face="arial"><i>NECROMANCER</span></td></tr></table></font></i></center><center><font face=arial></center><center><I>"My eyes will pierce your soul, then I will take your life!"</I></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/urheaton.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rheaton</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 212<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/4/02 8:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=67>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Waaaaaazup!</span><hr size=1> <br>
