I believe the Bible refers many times to slavery but never condemns it.  I think if God really did want freedom to rank up high, he would have put it in the 10 Commandments.  Lying and envy made it to the commandments but not slavery.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> How do we find fairness while maintaining freedom of religion and speech?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is pretty tough.  I think politically it has always been safe to appear Christian or devout.  In that way you fit within the majority and are more easily accepted.  Many of the founding fathers were Deists, Unitarians, freethinkers or sporatically Christian.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I did in fact classify an Atheist as one of no beliefs. The fact is that you do have a belief system or religion of sorts.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
