<br>
Even the more reason not to pray in public as an official, since it is a confession of <b>personal</b> beliefs. <b>Not</b> a confession of public beliefs.<br>
<br>
<i>"By praying aloud you are telling someone "this is what I believe".</i><br>
<br>
Many of us don't care, really. Personal beliefs are just that, personal.<br>
<br>
<i>"You are not telling someone "you are wrong."</i><br>
<br>
I believe you are understating the power one has when in public office, or when a public official. Especially the power one has over children. I don't know how old you are Rheaton, but when I was growing up if it was found out that a school teacher didn't support the Vietnam War, some of us children believed the teacher was a communist? Why? Because our elders in government told us so. Furthermore, you wouldn't believe how many people I have talked with arugue that the United States is a "Christian" country because we have "In God We Trust" minted on our currency. What does that say? Of course, it is a means to disenfranchise non-Christians. That is an abuse of power. I wouldn't expect you to see that, since you are part of the majority. All I can say is it is easy being in the majority, you don't have to see discrimination on religious grounds.<br>
<br>
<i>"Praying in the senate is telling everyone "this is my faith" and is not a denouncement of other faiths or beliefs."</i><br>
<br>
Why the hell can't people just <i>say</i> "this is what I believe" when <b>asked</b>? If praying is a personal confession, then I don't want to hear your prayers. Plain and simple. I also don't need you confessing to your god on my behalf. I don't need Christians praying for my children, too.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, when license is given for a senate prayer, it means that all involved should agree that the prayer is being given on their behalf. Right? But it is ludicrous to believe that not only everyone in the senate chamber believes about god in the same way as the prayer giver, but that the prayer is even efficacious for the public at large. Indeed, the arrogancy involved in thinking one can offer a public prayer on behalf of all Americans is mind boggling, at the least. <p><center><font face="arial" color="CCFFFF">Lurikeen Mali'Kyre</FONT></center><center><table style='Filter: Shadow(Color=#150517, Direction=225)'><tr><td><span class='Necromancer'><font size=2 color="red" face="arial"><i>NECROMANCER</span></td></tr></table></font></i></center><center><font face=arial></center><center><I>"My eyes will pierce your soul, then I will take your life!"</I></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uquath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Quath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 48<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/4/02 2:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=302.topic&index=73>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Waaaaaazup!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If the President were to go on TV and announce there is no God... he would be giving his opinion, but at the same time he would be refuting someone else's beliefs.... Praying aloud does not do that.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
