Imagine if the president were to televise a prayer to Allah (in Arabic?) or perhaps one of those prayers to Lucifer or the Horned God. Many Christians would be terribly offended and there would probably be a huge public outcry. Perhaps some would be more accepting of different religious views, but I suspect all would feel at least somewhat uncomfortable. All non-Christians are going to feel some of that discomfort whenever a public figure makes a statement or prayer which assumes the existance and worship of Jesus. Seeing &quot;In God We Trust&quot; on money may cause a similar feeling.<br>
<br>
The 1989 figures used in the 2001 in the CIA factbook list religious beliefs in the US as Protestant 56%, Roman Catholic 28%, Jewish 2%, other 4%, none 10%. It probably doesn't reflect as stronly on belief, but levels of church attendance are probably <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.religion-online.org/cgi-bin/relsearchd.dll/showarticle?item_id=237">much lower</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> than the 40% that these (voluntary) surveys report.<br>
